    content: `<div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">07 · Important Risks</div>
    <h2>Important Risks</h2>
    <p>These risks represent scenarios where key variables move adversely and the earnings outcome is materially worse than expected. Each is grounded in Pakistan's textile sector mechanics, not generic financial risk categories.</p>

    <div class="risk-list">

      <div class="risk-item">
        <div class="risk-name">EFS Distortion Persistence — Spinning Sector Collapse</div>
        <div class="risk-desc">The Export Facilitation Scheme's 18% GST on domestically purchased cotton vs 0% on imported Chinese cotton is destroying Pakistan's spinning industry at an accelerating rate. More than 100 spinning mills closed in 2025 and APTMA membership fell from 400 to under 200 active members. If the EFS distortion is not corrected — specifically if SRO 957(I)/2021 (which allowed local inputs to be zero-rated) is not reinstated — Pakistan risks permanently destroying its domestic cotton and spinning supply base. For composite mills with in-house spinning (NML, GATM), this creates an ongoing structural drag on the spinning segment's economics. For pure spinners, it is existential.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <div class="risk-name">Energy Tariff Escalation Under IMF Conditions</div>
        <div class="risk-desc">Gas tariff for captive power plants was raised to Rs4,291/mmbtu in March 2025, with further increases of 10%, 15%, and 20% scheduled in July 2025, February 2026, and August 2026 respectively under Pakistan's IMF programme. Pakistan's industrial electricity rate (~15.4 cents/kWh) is already approximately double Bangladesh's (~7 cents/kWh). These scheduled increases will widen Pakistan's energy cost disadvantage further, compressing margins across all energy-intensive production stages (spinning, weaving, dyeing). RCET (Regionally Competitive Energy Tariffs) — which previously offset this disadvantage — was discontinued under IMF pressure. Companies with solar or captive gas partially offset this; companies without are fully exposed.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <div class="risk-name">GSP+ Suspension or Non-Renewal by the EU</div>
        <div class="risk-desc">Pakistan's preferential (zero or reduced-duty) access to the EU — its largest textile export market at ~$3.67B — is governed by the GSP+ scheme, which requires compliance with 27 international conventions on governance, human rights, and labour standards. The EU conducts periodic reviews and can suspend or withdraw GSP+ if Pakistan fails to meet convention implementation benchmarks. A GSP+ suspension would impose standard EU tariffs on Pakistani textile exports — approximately 9–12% on garments — making Pakistani goods significantly less price-competitive vs Bangladesh (which also has GSP+ but is more advanced in compliance implementation). This risk is not imminent but is not zero.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <div class="risk-name">Western Consumer Spending Weakness</div>
        <div class="risk-desc">Pakistan's textile exporters are highly dependent on EU and US consumer spending on apparel and home textiles. A meaningful EU recession or US consumer pullback would reduce order volumes across the entire export sector. ILP is the most exposed by revenue concentration (90%+ Western brand revenues). NML, GATM, and SAPT are also significantly exposed, with GATM's "Ideas" domestic retail providing a partial offset. The Bangladesh windfall (order diversion during Bangladesh's political disruption in 2024) is a one-time event — any Bangladesh normalisation removes this tailwind and the baseline demand picture returns.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <div class="risk-name">Cotton Crop Failure and Supply Disruption</div>
        <div class="risk-desc">Pakistan's domestic cotton production has collapsed from ~15M bales historically to ~5–6M bales in FY25 — a 60–67% decade-long decline driven by climate stress, water scarcity, and shifting crop economics. FY25 saw an additional 34% YoY decline. If domestic cotton production continues declining, composites will be forced to import an increasing share of their cotton — increasing exposure to international price volatility, logistics costs, and the EFS distortion's GST cash-flow penalty on domestic purchases. Any major cotton crop failure driven by flood, drought, or pest outbreak would create an immediate input cost shock across the entire sector.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <div class="risk-name">Bangladesh and Vietnam Competitive Recovery</div>
        <div class="risk-desc">Bangladesh's political disruption in mid-2024 diverted textile orders to Pakistan — a windfall that contributed meaningfully to Pakistan's textile export growth in FY25. As Bangladesh stabilises politically and operationally, this diverted order flow will partially return to Bangladesh. Additionally, Vietnam continues to advance quality standards and is expanding its presence in European apparel markets. Pakistan's labour cost advantage over Bangladesh is narrow ($140/month vs $113/month minimum wage) and shrinking. Without sustained energy cost improvement and continued ESG investment, Pakistan's competitive position could erode as regional peers stabilise.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <div class="risk-name">Finance Cost Burden on Leveraged Composites</div>
        <div class="risk-desc">Pakistan's composite textile mills carry high leverage relative to other PSX sectors — textile machinery requires large upfront capital investment, and working capital needs (cotton purchasing, inventory, receivables) are substantial. NML's 35.1% earnings decline in FY25 reflected, in part, the accumulated impact of elevated finance costs from peak KIBOR periods (22%). While LTFF/ERF rate declines in 2024–25 have provided relief, companies that took on large debt at peak rates are still working through higher-cost legacy borrowing. Any reversal of the rate cut cycle — if inflation re-accelerates — would re-tighten finance costs on working capital facilities before long-term refinancing becomes available.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-item">
        <div class="risk-name">ESG Compliance Escalation (EU Regulations)</div>
        <div class="risk-desc">EU sustainability regulations are tightening rapidly — the EU's Corporate Sustainability Due Diligence Directive (CSDDD) and related regulations increasingly require Western retailers to demonstrate supply chain compliance on carbon, water, and labour standards. As these requirements escalate, textile companies without credible sustainability programmes risk being moved off approved vendor lists. ILP is well-positioned; NML, GATM, and SAPT are investing but remain behind ILP's LEED benchmark. Companies that do not maintain adequate ESG investment pace will face buyer concentration risk as retailers narrow their preferred vendor lists to compliance-certified suppliers.</div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>`,
